Sutton, Ruth DOB: 10/15/1947 (306794)
PATIENT NAME: Ruth Sutton DOB: 10/15/1947 AGE/SEX: 78yF LOCATION: 10280 Sheridan Blvd Room 130
Westminster, CO 80020 (Sunrise Westminster) ADMIT DATE: 12/11/25 CODE STATUS: DNR ALLERGIES:
none FACILITY INFORMATION Primary Contact: Natasha (Nurse) 701-202-6849 Second Contact:
Sammantha (Coordinator) 303-410-0500 FAX: 303-410-0600 PATIENT CONTACT/MDPOA NAME: Roy
Sutton RELATIONSHIP: brother PHONE: 720-320-6684 FREQUENCIES RN: 2 CNA: 2 NOTES FOR
CHAPLAIN: Pt is Baptist and open to chaplain visits. NOTES FOR SOCIAL WORK: Pt has no kids and has
never been married. Her younger brother is her POA. NOTES FOR CNA: Bed baths at this time. I think pt
would be too difficult to transfer to shower. Ruth is a 78yF admitted to hospice services with a primary
diagnosis of senile degeneration of the brain, supported by advanced cognitive impairment and significant
functional decline. Her medical history is notable for combined systolic and diastolic congestive heart failure
(LVEF 62%), chronic subdural hematoma, CKD stage 1, hyperlipidemia, hypothyroidism, cerebrovascular
disease, aortic atherosclerosis, hypertension, Type 2 myocardial infarction, and vascular dementia. Her
cognitive status has markedly worsened in recent months, with a SLUMS score of 16/30 and a FAST score
of 6E, demonstrating progression to moderately severe dementia. She is alert and oriented to person,
place, and time but displays increased confusion, new inability to operate everyday devices such as her
phone and TV remote, and intermittent delusional thinking. She recently reported that staff were hiding
under blankets in her room and were trying to get her. Speech remains clear. Functionally, the patient has
experienced a rapid and profound decline following multiple recent falls, one of which involved breaking a
glass cabinet and resulted in left rib and nasal bone fractures. Previously independent, she is now
wheelchair-bound, unable to ambulate, and fully dependent for 5 of 6 ADLs. She requires hands-on
assistance with bathing and dressing, is incontinent of both bowel and bladder, cannot turn herself in bed,
and is unable to sit upright without support. Transfers now require a newly initiated Hoyer lift,
demonstrating significant loss of strength and mobility. Although she can feed herself, she has increasing
difficulty reaching items, poor coordination, and frequently calls out for assistance when she is unable to
locate or grasp food or a water glass. She reports trouble swallowing pills. Meals are consumed at
approximately 50%. Weight is currently 172 lbs, with recent gain attributed to worsening fluid retention;
BMI is 30.7. Her PPS is 40%, consistent with reduced activity, extensive disease, and inability to perform
most self-care. She exhibits shallow breathing with diminished lung sounds, shortness of breath with
minimal exertion, and 3+ bilateral lower-extremity edema, occasionally weeping despite intensified diuretic
therapy. She remains on room air. Pain is primarily localized to the left hip, ranging from 2/10 to 5/10.
Sleep is estimated at approximately 10 hours out of 24. No current infections or wounds were noted,
however a full skin assessment was unable to be completed due to pt’s condition and inability to turn.
Overall, Ruth demonstrates a clear terminal decline consistent with senile degeneration of the brain,
evidenced by significant cognitive deterioration, impaired executive functioning, new inability to perform
familiar tasks, and rapid loss of mobility and independence. Her recent falls, worsening heart failure
symptoms, functional dependence, and progressive frailty further support a poor prognosis. Given her
declining trajectory, profound dependence, and advanced dementia, the patient meets hospice criteria and
is appropriate for end-of-life care focused on comfort and quality of life. ADMITTING DX: Senile
degeneration of the brain COMORBIDITIES: combined systolic and diastolic CHF, LVEF 62%, chronic
subdrual hematoma, CKD1, HLD, hypothyroidism, CVD, aortic atherosclerosis, HTN, MI Type 2, vascular
dementia, SLUMS 16/30 ADLS AMBULATION: wheelchair bound BATHING: needs assistance CONTINENCE:
incontinent of both urine and bowel DRESSING: needs assistance FEEDING: can feed self however pt is
having trouble reaching for items and overall poor eye-hand coordination and getting things to mouth.
TRANSFERS: needs assistance; requires hoyer lift (new) POSITIONING IN BED: cannot turn self in bed
ABLE TO SIT UP INDEPENDENTLY? Cannot sit up independently MENTAL STATE: A&Ox3; increased
confusion; cannot work everyday devices like phone and remote (new) SPEECH: clear
HALLUCINATIONS/DELUSIONS: delusions at times; thought staff was hiding under blanket in room waiting
to “get her” MEALS: 3 meals @ 50% WEIGHT: 172. WEIGHT LOSS: none; pt had weight gain due to fluid
retention HEIGHT: 5’4” BMI: 30.7 MAC: UTA DIET: regular DYSPHAGIA: none NAUSEA/VOMITING: none
SLEEP: 10/24 (hard to estimate) PAIN: left hip pain Worst pain: 5/10 Best pain: 2/10 Goal: 0/10 FALLS:
multiple falls; left rib fx; nasal bone fx INFECTIONS: none ADLS: 5/6 PPS: 40% FAST: 6E WOUNDS: none;
full skin check unable to be completed due to pt’s inability to move in bed-no staff available to assist
RESPIRATORY: RA EDEMA: 3+ to BLE; weeping at times; pt on double lasix with continued weight gain and
increased fluid retention LUNGS: diminished; shallow breaths CHANGE IN OXYGEN WITH ACTIVITY: SOB
