CHAPLAIN: Pt is Methodist and open to chaplain visits. NOTES FOR SOCIAL WORK: No immediate concerns.
NOTES FOR CNA: Pt can transfer to shower with 1 person assist. Sharon is a 76yF admitted to hospice
services with a primary diagnosis of diastolic congestive heart failure (HFpEF) and significant comorbidities
including hypertensive heart disease with heart failure, atrial fibrillation requiring pacemaker placement,
pulmonary hypertension, obstructive sleep apnea on CPAP, recurrent urinary tract infections,
hyperlipidemia, hypothyroidism, GERD, IBS, overactive bladder, and history of pneumonia. Most recent
echocardiogram shows preserved ejection fraction of 55–59%; however, patient demonstrates advanced
heart failure symptoms consistent with NYHA Class IV. She reports progressive and worsening shortness of
breath at rest and with minimal exertion, persistent fatigue, dizziness, recurrent angina, and significant
volume overload despite maximal medical therapy including furosemide, hydralazine, nitroglycerin,
metoprolol, and rivaroxaban. CT imaging revealed cardiomegaly, mild interstitial edema, and pulmonary
hypertension. Physical exam notable for diminished lung sounds, 3+ bilateral lower extremity edema, and
oxygen dependence at 2L via nasal cannula continuously, though patient reports intermittent
noncompliance. She experiences prolonged recovery time with any activity and requires head-of-bed
elevation to breathe comfortably. Functional assessment reveals a PPS of 50% with decline in ADLs,
currently requiring assistance with bathing and experiencing urinary and bowel incontinence with frequent
accidents. She is primarily wheelchair-bound, using a walker only for short distances, and spends the
majority of the day chair-bound. Despite being able to feed, dress, transfer, and reposition herself, she
reports increasing difficulty due to dyspnea, fatigue, and weakness. Left MAC measures 29 cm. Nutritional
intake is fair at approximately 75% of meals, with albumin decreased at 2.9, indicating poor nutritional
reserve. Patient endorses nausea and ongoing diarrhea and is requesting symptom management. She
reports abdominal and cardiac pain rated 4/10 at baseline with episodes reaching 8/10, with a goal of 0/10.
Patient is alert and oriented x3 with clear but hoarse speech and no evidence of hallucinations or delusions.
She reports sleeping approximately 6 hours per 24-hour period with frequent interruptions due to shortness
of breath. Recent hospitalizations include admission on 12/11 for crushing chest pain, shortness of breath,
and melena, during which hemoglobin dropped to 6.9 secondary to suspected gastrointestinal bleeding.
Creatinine is elevated at 1.85, indicating renal impairment likely related to cardiorenal syndrome. She has
had recent treatment for UTI, kidney infection, and pneumonia, reflecting increased vulnerability and
disease burden. Overall, Sharon meets hospice eligibility criteria due to end-stage diastolic heart failure
with NYHA Class IV symptoms, recurrent hospitalizations, treatment-resistant volume overload,
uncontrolled atrial fibrillation requiring pacemaker, dependence on continuous oxygen, significant functional
decline, evidence of poor nutritional status, and progression of symptoms despite optimal medical
management. She has expressed a clear desire to avoid further hospitalization and curative interventions,
electing comfort-focused care. Hospice services are appropriate to manage symptoms of dyspnea, pain,
edema, gastrointestinal distress, anxiety, and overall decline, and to support the patient’s stated goals of
care. ADMITTING DX: diastolic CHF COMORBIDITIES: hypertensive heart disease with heart failure,
preserved EF (55-59%) AFIB, pacemaker, history of recurrent UTI, OSA, OAB, HLD, IBS, hypothyroidism,
