88 year old male admitted to hospice with a primary diagnosis of senile dementia. Patient is noted to have
both short and long term memory impairments. Comorbidities include failure to thrive, hypertension,
vascular glaucoma resulting in blindness, coronary artery disease, anemia, history of fractures, and
generalized weakness. Patient resides in the memory care unit at San Mario ALF and presents with
progressive functional decline. Patient’s H&P reflects that he has had multiple ED visits in the past several
months with the most recent visit being on yesterday for evaluation of pelvic and sacral pain which is
chronic in nature. Per patient’s daughter, who is also MPOA the patient sustained a fall in May 2025 which
resulted in a coccyx fracture. She states that the pain related to the fracture has contributed to patient’s
discomfort and progressive physical decline. Daughter reports her dad has had multiple other falls within
the last six months as well a he is more confused about his ability to be independent. Staff at facility
attribute patient’s increase in falls to patient’s progressive weakness, increased confusion, and his
blindness and note that sometimes he is unable to remember where items are in his room. During visit
patient is sitting In his recliner and appears comfortable. Per staff, patient had a late dinner and was able
to eat approximately 75% of his meal which was a hamburger. Patient alert and oriented to person and
place and is unable to recall recent events from earlier this morning. He is unable to recall what he had for
dinner which was less than an hour ago. Patient has difficulty answering some questions during assessment
and is lethargic and falling asleep during assessment. ROS completed. Vital signs stable and within normal
limits for this patient. BBS diminished. No complaints of shortness of breath, chest pain, or cough. SPO2
97% RA. Patient is ambulatory with a walker and standby assistance and intermittently uses a wheelchair
due to increased weakness and fatigue. He denies any gastrointestinal issues. Per staff he uses a urinal but
has occasional urinary incontinence. Skin warm and dry with multiple random scratches to bilateral arms
and the right cheek. Patient is unable to recall how they occurred. Patient assessed for pain which he
denies during visit. Patient’s daughter reports patient will initially deny pain but will later acknowledge
discomfort when probed. POC, medication regime, safety precautions reviewed with facility staff. Advised
that patient is at high fall fish due to blindness, dementia, and impaired safety awareness. Encouraged to
monitor patient more frequently and provide close supervision with mobility. Verbalized understanding.
Educated daughter and staff regarding hospice protocol including emergency numbers with staff and
patient’s daughter.
