Assessment Summary Since Last Progress Report
Precautions Precautions: Fall risk and Confusion.
Skill Skilled Interventions Provided: During this reporting period, the physical therapy team has provided a multi-faceted
skilled program. Interventions have included therapeutic exercises with resistance bands and ankle weights to
improve bilateral lower-extremity strength, targeting the hip, knee, and ankle musculature. Neuromuscular
reeducation has been a significant focus, with the patient performing dynamic balance tasks on unstable surfaces
such as foam pads and DinaDisks. These tasks were progressed by incorporating head turns, gaze stabilization, and
multi-planar reaching to challenge vestibular balance, proprioception, and ankle strategies. Gait training has been
conducted on varied surfaces, including outdoor sidewalks and inclines, with skilled verbal and tactile cueing for
postural correction, trunk extension, and cadence changes. Therapeutic activities have focused on functional tasks,
such as sit-to-stand transfers from multiple surfaces without upper extremity support. Manual therapy techniques,
including soft-tissue mobilization of the lumbar spine and lower extremities and gentle joint mobilizations, were used
as needed to address the patient's complaints of pain and stiffness. The therapy team also provided crucial education
on fall risk reduction, proper home exercise performance, and environmental safety, including ensuring walker brakes
are locked during standing exercises.
Assessment Summary Since Eval/SOC
Response to Tx Progress & Response to Tx: The patient has demonstrated a variable response to therapy in this reporting period,
with recent objective measures indicating a functional decline. After showing initial progress as documented in the
10/10/2025 report, her most recent testing on 11/6/2025 revealed a regression in all primary outcome measures. Her
Five Times Sit-to-Stand time regressed from 12.0 seconds to 13.0 seconds. Her One Leg Stance time decreased
from 9 seconds to 5 seconds. Furthermore, her Six-Minute Walk Test score declined from a baseline of 225 meters to
188.97 meters, indicating a significant reduction in functional endurance. The patient continues to respond positively
to skilled cueing for postural correction during gait, but she requires these cues approximately 75% of the time to
maintain an upright trunk. Her cognitive impairment impacts carryover, as she demonstrates apprehension with
unsupported balance tasks and requires verbal cues for pathfinding in familiar environments.
Background Hx/Med Hx
Background Patient Behaviors: The patient consistently presents as pleasant and cooperative with therapy interventions.
Hx/Med Hx However, she exhibits notable apprehension and nervousness when performing dynamic balance tasks, particularly
when support is removed. Her ""Confusion"" precaution is evident, as she has required verbal cues for pathfinding even
on familiar routes. She requires consistent cueing from the therapy team to slow her movements, engage her core,
and maintain correct posture.
