Initial Assessment / Current Level of Function & Underlying Impairments
Patient Referral and History
Hx/Complexities Current Hx/Problem: Kimbrough Gregory, an 86-year-old male with a complex medical history, was evaluated on
June 30, 2025, for ongoing management of multiple chronic conditions. The patient resides at an assisted living
facility and receives primary care through home visits. His history was obtained from both the patient and the facility
staff.
Mr. Gregory has a known diagnosis of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and is oxygen-dependent. At
the time of evaluation, he denied experiencing increased shortness of breath, cough, sputum production, or fever. He
also has a history of chronic heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (HFpEF), but reported no chest pain,
worsening edema, dizziness, or recent falls.
On examination, he appeared elderly but in no acute distress, easily arousable from sleep. Cardiovascular
assessment revealed a regular rhythm with a systolic murmur. The pulmonary exam showed clear but diminished
breath sounds, without signs of increased work of breathing. His abdomen was protuberant, and he had mild (1+)
peripheral edema. Neurologically, he was noted to be pleasantly confused, consistent with his diagnosis of moderate
Alzheimer’s dementia.. He can ambulate slowly with a walker, though he remains at high risk for respiratory infections
and functional decline.
Mr. Gregory’s current problems include COPD, chronic hypoxic respiratory failure, dependence on continuous
supplemental oxygen, secondary hyperaldosteronism, HFpEF, and moderate Alzheimer’s dementia. Additional
comorbidities include coronary artery disease, hyperlipidemia, atrial fibrillation, hypertension, benign prostatic
hyperplasia, dysphagia, seasonal allergic rhinitis, GERD, stage 3a chronic kidney disease, and a history of transient
ischemic attack. He's status post aortic valve replacement and pacemaker implantation, and is dependent on a
wheelchair for mobility.
This comprehensive clinical picture underscores the need for coordinated multidisciplinary care, including physical,
occupational, and speech therapy, to support his functional status and quality of life.
