Assessment
Impressions Clinical Impressions: Kimbrough Gregory is an 86-year-old male with a complex medical history including COPD,
chronic hypoxic respiratory failure, HFpEF, Alzheimer’s dementia, and multiple cardiovascular comorbidities. He
presents with significant functional limitations and mobility impairments.
The patient completed a Timed Up and Go (TUG) test in 33 seconds, which is significantly below the normative
threshold and indicates an elevated risk for falls. His Berg Balance Scale (BERG) score was 36, consistent with
moderate fall risk and impaired balance. Additionally, the 6-Minute Walk Test (6MWT) yielded a distance of 110
meters, reflecting markedly reduced endurance and limited exercise tolerance.
Manual muscle testing (MMT) of the bilateral lower extremities revealed strength of 4/5 throughout, suggesting mild
generalized weakness. Despite these physical limitations, the patient denies any current pain.
These findings, in the context of his medical complexity and cognitive impairment, underscore the need for skilled
physical, occupational, and speech therapy services to address fall risk, mobility deficits, endurance limitations, and
safety concerns in the home environment.
Skilled Need Skilled Justification: Physical therapy is medically necessary for Kimbrough Gregory due to his complex medical
history and current functional impairments. Mr. Gregory is an 86-year-old male with chronic obstructive pulmonary
disease (COPD), chronic hypoxic respiratory failure, heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (HFpEF), and
moderate Alzheimer's dementia, among other comorbidities. These conditions contribute to significant limitations in
his mobility, balance, and endurance, placing him at elevated risk for falls and further functional decline.
Recent functional assessments highlight the extent of his impairments. He completed the Timed Up and Go (TUG)
test in 33 seconds, which is well above the threshold for fall risk in older adults and indicates a high likelihood of
falling. His Berg Balance Scale score was 36, consistent with moderate fall risk and impaired postural control.
Additionally, his performance on the 6-Minute Walk Test (6MWT) was limited to 110 meters, reflecting significantly
reduced endurance and exercise tolerance. Manual muscle testing of the bilateral lower extremities revealed 4/5
strength throughout, suggesting mild generalized weakness. Despite these physical limitations, Mr. Gregory denies
any current pain, which supports his potential to participate in therapy actively.
Given these findings, skilled physical therapy is required to address his deficits in strength, balance, and endurance.
A licensed physical therapist is needed to develop and implement an individualized treatment plan, monitor the
patient's response to interventions, and ensure safety during mobility training. Therapy will also focus on fall
prevention strategies, caregiver education, and improving functional independence within his assisted living
environment. The complexity of his medical and functional status necessitates skilled intervention to prevent further
decline and promote quality of life.
