Initial Assessment / Current Level of Function & Underlying Impairments
Assessment Summary
Clinical Clinical Impressions: Patient is a cooperative, guarded, 95 yo female resident of Golden Pond ALF who self reports
Impressions difficulty swallowing some foods. Patient states spicy foods are difficult to swallow, sometimes pills. Patient is
talkative and opinionated throughout session.
Reason for Skilled Justification: Skilled ST services addressing dysphagia, oral motor function, diet/texture analysis, patient and
Therapy caregiver education. This intervention is medically necessary in order to improve strength and safety of swallow
function, decreased risk of aspiration/penetration and to improve quality of life related to PO intake.
Risk Factors Risk Factors: dementia, dysphagia
Plan Focus Focus of Plan of Treatment = Compensation,Adaptation
Recommendations
Further Testing MBS/FEES/ENT/GI Indicated = No
Further exam/consult not indicated d/t: = Swallow therapy is indicated prior to exam to increase ability to participate
with objective testing.
Intake Diet Recs - Solids = Regular textures
Diet Recs - Liquids = Cup drinking
Supervision Supervision for Oral Intake = No supervision/assistance required
Strategies Comp Strategies/Positions: SAFER SWALLOW STRATEGIES
1) Small bites and small, single sips. Eat and drink slowly.
2) Chew your food thoroughly and swallow what's in your mouth before you take another bite or a sip of liquid. Small
bite sized pieces are most easily negotiated in the oral cavity.
3) NO talking with food in your mouth
4)Alternate solids and liquids - every two bites, after you have chewed and swallowed all the food in your mouth, take
a sip.
5) UP at 90' for all PO intake (food, drink and meds) and for 30-60 minutes after
6) Meds one at a time with water or applesauce as appropriate
7) Thorough oral hygiene, frequency as recommended by SLP
