Assessment Summary Since Last Progress Report
Precautions Precautions: Fall risk, legally blind, colostomy.
Skill Skilled Interventions Provided: Cognitive Skills Development: Establishment of compensatory techniques to increase
skills, Development of/instruction in cueing hierarchy to increase functional abilities, Facilitation of anticipatory
problem solving and Graded cueing to improve problem solving Training in use of visual/environmental aids to
facilitate increased functional skills. Speech Therapy: Exercises to increase naming/word finding skills.
Assessment Summary Since Eval/SOC
Response to Tx Progress & Response to Tx: Patient's condition has potential to improve as a result of skilled rehab.
Objective Tests and Measures
Other Other Tests Completed: Mini-Cog + informal language assessment
Score Interpretation: Patient was administered the Mini-Cog to assess cognitive function including immediate/delayed
recall and visuospatial abilities. Patient immediately recalled 3/3 words, indicating intact initial encoding. Following a
brief delay, patient was unable to independently recall any of the words; however, she was able to recall 2/3 words
with mod-max verbal cues, suggesting significant deficits in delayed recall and retrieval of newly learned information.
During the clock drawing task, patient was able to place numbers on the clock face, though number placement was
disorganized and not within appropriate spatial locations. Patient was unable to mark the designated time.
Performance was impacted by patient’s severe visual impairment, requiring increased lighting and assistance with
orienting to the circle to locate number positions. Results are indicative of impairments in visuospatial processing,
executive functioning, and memory.
Patient completed informal confrontation naming in her apartment using familiar, functional items. She demonstrated
9/10 accuracy, indicating largely intact object recognition and expressive vocabulary at the single-word level.
Occasional delays were observed but improved with additional time. Receptive comprehension appeared grossly
functional for simple questions and conversation, though further structured assessment may be warranted to fully
evaluate comprehension and higher-level language processes.
Findings from the Mini-Cog and informal language tasks indicate moderate to severe cognitive impairment, primarily
affecting memory consolidation, visuospatial skills, and executive functioning. Language skills at the basic level
remain mostly intact, supporting potential for continued participation in functional cognitive-communication therapy.
Visual impairment significantly affects performance and will require ongoing environmental and visual cueing supports
in therapy.
Justification for Reasonable and Necessary Services
Continued Skill Reason for Skilled Services: In order to prevent decline in function, patient requires continued ST services to enhance
cognitive skills, improve language function, facilitate orientation abilities, enhance short-term memory, increase verbal
problem solving and promote safety awareness/insight.
