Assessment Summary
Impressions Clinical Impressions: Fred is an 81 year old male patient whom resides at MorningStar Arvada in the memory care
unit with his wife whom assists as his caregiver and is being evaluated for outpatient physical therapy today following
a hospitalization secondary to a vertebral artery thrombosis. Fred is currently on eliquis and has a follow up with his
doctor in a few weeks per the patient’s wife reports. Fred has a PMH signficant for: vertebral artery thrombosis,
Subarachnoid hemorrhage, parkinson’s disease, diabetes, HTN. Patient uses a wheelchair as his primary mode of
mobility, though also uses a U-Step walker for ambulation. Patient’s wife reports that the patient is only to be
ambulating during therapy at this time. Upon assessment today, patient requires SBA and increased time for
transfers; CGA for ambulation with his U-step walker and requires cues for safety with device; presents with decrased
muscle strength in (B) LE with MMT and low 30 second chair rise score; is at an incrased risk for falls as suggested
by his Tinetti score, TUG time, and BERG balance score; and presents with low ambulation capacity as demonstrated
by his 6MWT distance.
Skilled Need Skilled Justification: Skilled physical therapy is reasonable and medically necessary in order to address this patient’s
deficits and limitations, allowing for increased safety and independence with functional daily activities and mitigate
risk for falls.
