Assessment
Impressions Clinical Impressions: Larry is an 84 year old male patient being evaluated for outpatient physical therapy care today
due to weakness and instability in the right lower extremity and knee. Patient sustained an infection in his spine in
August of this year, per his reports, that resulted in weakness and reduced sensation in the right leg. He states it
began in his low back and torso region and now his experiencing pain up to 9/10 in his knee that is exacerbated by
walking. Patient reports he is also now experiencing cervical radiculopathy into the right hand, but states his focus is
on this lower body. Larry has a significant PMH that can be located in the first section of this evaluation. Patient was
previously ambulating without an assistive devices, though now is using a cane due to instability. Patient reports he
worries about falling. Upon assessment today, patient does not present with any pain with palpation to the right knee
though does present with reduced sensation throughout the medial right LE; he presents with gross weakness in the
LE with functional strength testing of the 30 second chair rise test; he presents with reduced ambulation capacity as
noted by the 6MWT, and is at an increased risk for falls as indicated by his BERG balance score.
Skilled Need Skilled Justification: Skilled physical therapy is reasonable and medically necessary in order to address this patient’s
deficits and limitations, allowing for increased safety and independence and return to prior level of function.
