Objective Tests and Measures
FAST FAST =
Other Other Tests Completed: Mini-Cog and informal cognitive tasks
Score Interpretation: The Mini-Cog was administered to assess cognitive function, including memory and visuospatial
skills. The patient demonstrated intact immediate recall, recalling 3/3 target words when presented. However,
following a brief delay, the patient recalled 0/3 words independently, indicating impaired delayed recall. With moderate
verbal cueing, recall improved to 3/3, suggesting benefit from external supports and cueing strategies.
During the clock drawing task, the patient was unable to draw a recognizable clock face or accurately place or label
the time, reflecting deficits in visuospatial construction and executive functioning.
Additional cognitive tasks were completed for a broader assessment of cognitive-linguistic skills. The patient
generated 14 category members (animals) within one minute, which is below age-expected norms and suggests
reduced verbal fluency and generative language skills.
Orientation assessment revealed the patient to be correctly oriented to place, spouse, children, and general time of
day, but not oriented to month, year, or age, which is consistent with impaired temporal and personal orientation.
Overall, results are indicative of moderate cognitive deficits affecting delayed memory, visuospatial skills, executive
functioning, and orientation. Continued skilled speech-language pathology intervention is recommended to target
memory strategy use, functional orientation, and cognitive-communication skills to promote safety and independence.
Assessment Summary
Clinical Clinical Impressions: This 80 yo male presents with moderate cognitive impairment characterized by deficits in
Impressions delayed memory, visuospatial construction, executive functioning, verbal fluency, and temporal orientation.
Performance on the Mini-Cog revealed intact immediate recall but absent delayed recall without cueing, indicating
impaired retention and reduced ability to utilize internal memory strategies. Clock drawing performance was
significantly impaired, consistent with visuospatial and sequencing deficits. Verbal fluency was reduced, with a total of
14 animals named in one minute, suggesting decreased generative language and reduced processing efficiency.
Orientation assessment showed partial orientation, with preserved knowledge of familiar people and place, while
difficulties with month, year, and age reflect impaired temporal and self-related orientation. The patient demonstrated
improved recall with moderate cueing, indicating potential to benefit from structured compensatory strategies and
external memory supports.
Given these findings, the patient would benefit from ongoing skilled speech-language pathology intervention to
address memory strategy training, functional recall, orientation, executive functioning, and safety-related problem
solving to support independence with daily routines and reduce cognitive breakdowns during functional tasks.
Reason for Skilled Justification: Patient requires skilled SLP services for cognition/communication to minimize the risk for
Therapy dehydration enhance cognitive skills, facilitate orientation abilities and develop & instruct in compensatory strategies.
Risk Factors Risk Factors: Due to the documented physical impairments and associated functional deficits, without skilled
therapeutic intervention, the patient is at risk for: Decreased participation with functional tasks, Further decline in
function, Social isolation, Anxiety and Increased dependency upon caregivers.
