Recertification Visit Date of visit: 8/4/25 Patient: Doris Friedah Terminal Dx: Heart failure Co-morbidities:
chronic pain, FTT, hx NSTEMI, L heel p/u, chronic respiratory failure, CKD3, interstitial pulmonary disease,
polyneuropathy, urinary retention, hypertensive heart and CKD with HF, cognitive communication deficits,
AFIB, PVD, DM2, mitral valve disease, aortic atherosclerosis, pulmonary HTN, daytime somnolence, spinal
stenosis, CAD Recertification period #4 Weight: on admit 192lbs Last recert: 184lbs Current: unable to
obtain MAC: on admit 28cm Last recert: 27.5cm Current: 27.5cm ADL’s: admit 5/6 can feed self Last
recert: 5/6 Current: 5/6 PPS: admit 50% Last recert: 40% Current: 40% INTAKE: admit 50-75% of 2
meals Last recert: 50-75% of 2 meals Current: 25-50% of 2 meals HOURS OF SLEEP: 10-12 hours Last
recert: 10-12 hours Current: 14 hours FUNCTIONAL ABILITY: admit pivot to wheelchair Last recert: pivot
to wheelchair Current: pivot to wheelchair COGNITION: admit self/place Last recert: self/place
Current:self/place CONTINENCE: occasional urine incontinence SKIN/WOUNDS: stage 2 pressure injury to
heel, new stage 2 to back of thigh, new stage 2 to gluteal fold PAIN: requires PRN Norco daily, scheduled
lyrics, OxyContin FALLS: none INFECTIONS: several UTIs and yeast infections this cert, patient frequently
refusing antibiotics and having to restart course OXYGEN: 5L continuous, needs portable oxygen
concentrator within reach due to anxiety. Frequently complains of shortness of breath but refusing
morphine at this time CHANGES IN MEDICATION: several animation courses and antifungal courses, baza
cream for wound change to miconazole powder. Patient agreeable to deprescription of several vitamins this
cert due to increasing nausea and use of PRN zofran, would like to decrease pill burden. Narrative: patient
is an 89F with a primary diagnosis of HF with significant decline this benefit period warranting hospice
recertification. Patient with worsening BLE edema this cert, patient required 5 day increase of torsemide
that provided little to no improvement in edema. Patient with worsening skin breakdown this cert, new
stage 2 pressure injuries to gluteal fold and back of thigh, non healing wound to r heel despite optimal
wound care. Patient with increased lethargy, now sleeping 14 hours/day. Patient with increased nausea this
cert, requiring PRN zofran nearly daily after taking medications. Patient with decreased appetite, now
eating 25-50% of 2 meals daily. Patient with several UTIs and yeast infections, pateint unable to finish
course of antibiotics due to severe nausea however patients daughter convinced patient to start and finish
a new course of antibiotics. Heart and bowel sounds WNL. Lung sounds diminished. Patient with 4+ edema
to BLE. Daughter concerned for impending death as patient is starting to talk about death more frequently,
telling family to “stay away” so they don’t see her “like this”.
